This will be a walk through guide explaining the multiple plate reader data code and how to run it. 

I will be assuming that you have worked with single plate reader data script, and you have python and/or
jupyter installed, know how to set up virtual environments, and know how to run .ipynb files

Step 1:
  Downloading the file from github
  file is titled "kamariza_lab_graphing_multiple_plate_reader_data.ipynb"

Step 2:
  Make sure you have all the necessary files
  Layout files (saved as .csv, .txt)
  data files (saved as .csv, .txt)

Step 3:
  Opening File in perferable Jupyter notebook while in a virtual environment

Step 4:
  Run the imports cell

Step 5:
  determine how many distinct plates you will be importing
    if you have n number of plate, ensure that you are importing 2n files
    determine the file path and input it into the correct position
    also ensure that you are reading the correct number of plate and layouts

  if you are reading n number of plates, in this cell you should have 4n lines of code

Step 6:
  Creating a dictionary of the plate data and layout that correspond to one another
  Note this is 0 indexed
  copy and paste "0: [df_plate_reader_layout_0, df_plate_reader_data_0]," for as many plates you have
  ensure you change the number to correspond to the correct imported files

Step 7:
  Run all of the cells until step 8
  these cells contain the functions that we will be using

Step 8:
  run the cell containing
  "df = developing_new_df_from_multi_input_data(a_dict_of_all_data)"
  this calls the function developing_new_df_from_multi_input_data using the input a_dict_of_all_data
  which is the dictionary of all of the plate reader data and layout

Step 9:
  Visualize the dataframe by running the cell 
  print(df)
  visualize the column titles by the line
  print(df.columns)
  this will help in identifying misnamed columns

Step 10:
  in the list titled "similar_names" Identify all of the names (of the columns) that have been named
  differently, but indeed they are the same
  seperate these names by a comma

  In the list "wanted_names" in the exact same order, identify all of the titles which you wish to have

Step 11:
  run the cell containing "df = renaming_columns_of_a_dataframe(df, similar_names, wanted_names)"
  this uses the dataframe created in step 8, and the lists created in step 10, this cell will identify
  all of the columns that are desired to be called the same, and rearranges the columns and renames 
  the given column to what the user wished

Step 12:
  If you made dilutions and want to back calculate, continue, if not skip to step 13
  identify the columns names that need to be adjusted, and add this to the list 
  titled "columns_need_to_be_adjusted"
  in the same order identify the dilution factor and write it in the form X:Y 
  eg 1:10 = 10x, or 1:5 = 5x
  also change the final volume in ml
  next, run the cell containing "df = calculate_the_original_density(df,columns_need_to_be_adjusted, diluted_from_original_density, final_volume_in_ml)"

Step 13:
  following along identical to the single plate reader file, graph the data
  will update with more complicated graphs
  change the necessary details to get the desired graph(s)

